<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="220" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,258,1191]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,461,1059,1084]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
This is the third of the group of species with a cuboidal basiphallus, the others being 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Fulgenta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="complexa" status="sp. nov">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">F. complexa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[266,348,1096,1119]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" rank="species">sp. nov</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[404,528,1094,1119]" class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Fulgenta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plumosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[404,528,1094,1119]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">F. plumosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[536,627,1094,1119]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[536,627,1094,1119]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
It is has the longest cerci of these species and the surstylus is similarly reasonably well developed. It is however easily distinguished by the distinct cerci and phallus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
